> Patch Set 7:

> Hi,

> I'd like some more clarity here. Can you clarify why share network subnets isn't sufficient for this? I'd like to understand the use case here, and figure out what we missed when designing: https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/manila-specs/specs/train/share-network-multiple-subnets.html - (https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/manila/+/671043)

Hi,
As per https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/manila-specs/specs/train/share-network-multiple-subnets.html
when replica is created and it inherited parent shares share-network, manila will chose valid subnet and replica can be created within different availability zone against availability zone of share.

However there are use case where share network is different as said in bug e.g.
1. customer (non-admin) driven migration from one share network to another share network via replication
2. Network setup that has different neutron networks per availability zone (and therefore different) share networks and also wants to have replication setup between those two zones

> 
> However there are use case where share network is different as said in bug e.g.
> 1. customer (non-admin) driven migration from one share network to another share network via replication
> 2. Network setup that has different neutron networks per availability zone (and therefore different) share networks and also wants to have replication setup between those two zones

Hmm, by migration you mean the ability to preserve the share in the same AZ but move to a different share server and/or storage backend. The share networks API prevents adding more than one subnet for a given AZ within a share network: https://github.com/openstack/manila/blob/14d3e268a05265db53b5cfd19d9a85a3ba73a271/manila/api/v2/share_network_subnets.py#L107-L130

Lets brainstorm this a bit - (Carlos please jump in, since you're best acquainted with the DHSS=True mode of replication) can you think of any reason we must not allow different share instances within a share to be exported on separate share networks? One big reason is the ability to have the same security services - we take this for granted if we inherit a share's share_network when creating a replica - however, if we allow replicas in different share networks, we ought to atleast be sure the security services on these networks match. 

We also need tempest tests for both cases - i.e., ones where we're replicating shares across share networks, and ones where we're replicating across subnets in a given network.

One big reason is the ability to have the same security services - we take this for granted if we inherit a share's share_network when creating a replica - however, if we allow replicas in different share networks, we ought to atleast be sure the security services on these networks match.

Yes, I think the security service association would be the thing to worry about here... I was checking the code and going though our operations to allow access, and I trying to identify if a scenario where we have the same security service types for both share networks but we have different attributes for server (domain, user, password and so on) would be a problem... Manila seems to handle this pretty well, and it shouldn't be a problem. But we should definitely ensure that the security services in the former share network are in the new share network as well.

Besides that, since you would be adding an entire share network, I believe other check should be performed too (in the share replicas API or share/api operation to create share replicas), which would be to ensure that the new share network has a subnet in the same AZ as the former, or if it has a default share network. If this is not satisfied, the request should be denied...

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

This spec doesn't really spell out the details and implications of how this works...

If you revert to an older snapshots, are the newer snapshots all still fully functional on the backend?  Can you revert to an older snapshot and then revert to a newer snapshot?  How do we know what works on each backend?

Are we going to support a generic mechanism to copy data around for backends that can't natively do this?

We may want a config option for deployments to not allow reverting to older snapshots if the operator decides that it has excessive performance overhead.

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

We are now in the spec freeze for Victoria.  You may continue to work on this spec for Wallaby.

In addition to the comments on this review, it would be good if you could give some details on what happens on a typical backend that can do this in the ideal way.  What happens to the more recent snapshots if you revert to an older snapshot?

Patch Set 9:

> Patch Set 9:
> 
> We discussed this spec at the Wallaby PTG.  Please address the points outlined in the summary:
> https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/CinderWallabyPTGSummary#Support_revert_any_snapshot_to_the_volume
> 
> Thanks!
Ok, about the discussion in PTG. I have the following thoughts
1. About how to handle the performance problems with the generic，We can set a switch, which is turned on by default
2. About the revert chain, if the 3 is reverting, in the storage management, they can not revert to 7;
3. I think not all the storage vendors design snapshots as tree, perhaps the internal tree, but there are no restrictions on operation. Like this, there are three snapshots of volume: snap1, snap2, snap3, we can delete snap1 in the storage management.
4. It is possible to design an interface to realize whether the revert operation is supported by the driver
